# TypeScript patterns

## Module augmentation with concrete implementations

When a class has both a concrete implementation file (`.ts`) and a module augmentation declaration (`index.d.ts`), define all public fields and method signatures explicitly on **both sides**. The declaration in the augmentation must match the implementation exactly.

Private fields, getters, and methods do **not** require explicit return type annotations in the implementation — let TypeScript infer them. The module augmentation only declares the public API; private members are omitted entirely.

Example: [`src/lib/@thatopen/components/GeneralEditor.ts`](../../src/lib/@thatopen/components/GeneralEditor.ts) (implementation) + [`src/types/@thatopen/components/index.d.ts`](../../src/types/@thatopen/components/index.d.ts) (augmentation).
